# CLARA — Clinical AI Assistant for Cardiovascular Case Assessment

A hybrid AI assistant for doctors. Combines rule-based clinical logic,
structured lab extraction, and a local LLM to support cardiovascular
case assessment.

---

## Project Structure

clara-system/
├── backend/                        # C# — PDF ingestion only, this finds all the PDFs across all folders
│   ├── Controllers/
│   │   └── PdfIngestionController.cs
│   ├── Ingestion/
│   │   ├── PdfIngestionService.cs
│   │   └── PdfParser.cs
│   └── Program.cs
│
├── ai-services/                    # Python — all intelligence
│   ├── medical_text_api.py         # Text cleaning and lab extraction (port 8000)
│   ├── lab_extractors.py           # Regex-based lab value parser
│   ├── llm_service/
│   │   ├── llm_client.py           # LLM chat service with MCP tool loop (port 8001)
│   │   └── mcp_tools.py            # Tool definitions and executor
│   ├── ml_service/
│   │   └── app.py                  # ML prediction service (port 8002, placeholder)
│   └── rule_engine/
│       └── rules.py                # Rule-based clinical flag engine
│
├── frontend/                       # UI (not yet connected)
├── .venv/                          # Python virtual environment
└── README.md

---

## Services and Ports

| Port | Language | Service | Purpose |
|------|----------|---------|---------|
| 5000 | C# | PDF Ingestor | Reads PDFs from patient folders, returns raw text |
| 8000 | Python | Medical Text API | Cleans text, extracts and structures lab values |
| 8001 | Python | LLM Service | MCP tool loop, context injection, Ollama chat |
| 8002 | Python | ML Service | Risk prediction (placeholder) |
| 11434 | — | Ollama | Local LLM engine (llama3.2:1b) |

---

## Patient Folder Structure

Desktop/
└── Patients/
└── 00001/
├── demographics/
├── discharge/      ← PDF discharge summaries
├── encounters/
├── imaging/
├── labs/           ← PDF lab results (chemistry, hematology, microscopy)
└── prescriptions/

## How to Run

### Prerequisites
- .NET SDK installed
- Python 3.11+
- Ollama installed — https://ollama.com
- llama3.2:1b model pulled

### Pull the model (first time only)
```powershell
ollama pull llama3.2:1b
```

### Step 1 — Start Ollama
Ollama runs automatically on Windows after install.
To start manually:
```powershell
ollama serve
```
If you see "address already in use" it is already running. Proceed to Step 2.

### Step 2 — Start C# backend
```powershell
cd C:\clara-system\backend
dotnet run
```
Runs on http://localhost:5000

### Step 3 — Activate Python virtual environment
```powershell
cd C:\clara-system
.venv\Scripts\activate
```
You should see `(.venv)` at the start of your prompt.

### Step 4 — Start medical text API
Open a new terminal, activate venv, then:
```powershell
cd C:\clara-system\ai-services
uvicorn medical_text_api:app --port 8000 --reload
```

### Step 5 — Start LLM service
Open a new terminal, activate venv, then:
```powershell
cd C:\clara-system\ai-services\llm_service
uvicorn llm_client:app --port 8001 --reload
```

---

## Testing with Postman

### Health checks (run these first)
GET http://localhost:8000/
GET http://localhost:8001/health

### Extract chemistry lab results
POST http://localhost:8000/chemistry-results
Content-Type: application/json
{
"patient": "00001",
"labs": "chemistry"
}

### Extract hematology lab results
POST http://localhost:8000/hematology-results
Content-Type: application/json
{
"patient": "00001",
"labs": "hematology"
}

### Extract microscopy lab results
POST http://localhost:8000/microscopy-results
Content-Type: application/json
{
"patient": "00001",
"labs": "microscopy"
}

### Categorize all patient text
POST http://localhost:8000/categorize
Content-Type: application/json
{
"patient": "00001",
"labs": "labs"
}

### Chat with CLARA (main endpoint)
POST http://localhost:8001/chat
Content-Type: application/json
{
"patient_id": "00001",
"message": "What are this patient's cholesterol and creatinine levels?"
}

Expected response shape:
```json
{
  "patient_id": "00001",
  "response": "CREATININE is within normal range at 1.16 mg/dL...",
  "tools_called": ["get_chemistry"]
}
```


## How CLARA Works

1. Doctor sends a question and patient ID to the LLM service at port 8001
2. LLM service builds a prompt with tool definitions and sends it to Ollama
3. Ollama decides which tool to call based on the question
4. LLM service executes the tool — calls port 8000 to get structured lab data
5. Port 8000 calls C# at port 5000 to get raw PDF text
6. C# reads the PDF files from disk and returns raw text
7. Port 8000 cleans and extracts structured lab values
8. Lab data is injected into the prompt as patient context
9. Ollama generates a clinical response grounded in the actual data
10. Doctor receives the response with a list of which tools were called

---



## Current Limitations

- Model is llama3.2:1b — small and fast but limited reasoning ability
- No conversation history between requests — each chat is stateless
- Rule engine not yet connected to lab values
- ML service is a placeholder — no real model trained yet
- No frontend connected to the chat endpoint yet

